"'''Song Beneath the Song'''" (also known as '''''Grey's Anatomy'': The Music Event''') is the eighteenth episode of the [[Grey's Anatomy (season 7)|seventh season]] of the American medical drama ''[[Grey's Anatomy]]'', and the one-hundred and fourty-fourth episode overall. It was named after a song by American singer [[Maria Taylor]]. Written by series creator [[Shonda Rhimes]] and directed by [[Tony Phelan]], it premiered on [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]] in the United States on March 31, 2011. It is the series' first musical episode, and features the cast performing songs previously featured within the program. It is accompanied by a [[soundtrack album]], ''Grey's Anatomy: The Music Event'', also released on March 31, 2011.

The episode revolves around [[Callie Torres]] and [[Arizona Robbins]], just after they engage in a vehicular collision. Various songs are performed by the cast members, as they attempt to save the life of Torres. Rhimes originally idealized the episode at the conception of the drama, while the show remained untitled. The episode opened to mix reviews from television critics, and it was the second most watched program of the night. "Song Beneath the Song" was ranked in several "best and worst" lists, and the soundtrack was included on the [[Billboard 200]].

==Plot==
En-route to a weekend breakaway, surgeons [[Arizona Robbins]] ([[Jessica Capshaw]]) and [[Callie Torres]] ([[Sara Ram<U+00ED>rez]]) are involved in a vehicular collision, moments after Robbins proposes marriage. Torres suffers severe injuries, which endanger her life and her unborn child. She and Robbins are taken to Seattle Grace Mercy West Hospital, the institute at which they both work. Their colleagues attempt to save Torres, while Robbins and [[Mark Sloan (Grey's Anatomy)|Mark Sloan]] ([[Eric Dane]]), the father of Torres' baby, stand by. Torres' many injuries include neurological trauma. While barely conscious, she hallucinates an uninjured version of herself standing beside her. The hallucinatory Torres begins to sing, and is gradually joined by the doctors treating her. This singing continues throughout the episode, as Torres' projection of herself attempts to reach out to Robbins.

Torres goes into [[cardiac arrest]] and is taken into theatre, where she is temporarily stabilized, pending further surgery. She is moved into [[intensive care]], while neonatal surgeon [[Addison Montgomery]] ([[Kate Walsh (actress)|Kate Walsh]]) is flown in by helicopter in case the baby has to be delivered prematurely. Robbins and Sloan argue over Torres treatment; Robbins believes that Torres would not risk endangering the baby, but Sloan argues for saving Torres at all costs. The [[Attending physician|attending]] surgeons devise a treatment plan, led by trauma surgeon [[Owen Hunt]] ([[Kevin McKidd]]). As they do so, Torres dreams about the moments preceding the accident. Her dream self sings to Robbins, interspersed with shots of the hospital staff singing and dancing with their own partners. Hunt's wife [[Cristina Yang]] ([[Sandra Oh]]) suggests treating Torres with a high-risk but potentially effective [[Cardiothoracic surgery|cardiothoracic procedure]] she learned from her old mentor, [[Preston Burke]] ([[Isaiah Washington]]). Her current mentor, [[Teddy Altman]] ([[Kim Raver]]), refuses to perform it, but when Torres' condition deteriorates and she is rushed back into theatre, Hunt agrees that Yang should attempt the procedure.

When Torres again goes into cardiac arrest, Montgomery delivers her daughter at twenty-three weeks gestation. The baby is not initially able to breathe, so with Sloan's support, Robbins steps in and is able to revive her. Across the operating room, Torres' condition begins to improve. Once the surgery is complete, the doctors deal with their own affairs; Sloan's former partner [[Lexie Grey]] ([[Chyler Leigh]]) commits to her new relationship with resident [[Jackson Avery]] ([[Jesse Williams (actor)|Jesse Williams]]); Lexie's sister [[Meredith Grey]] ([[Ellen Pompeo]]) confesses that she was jealous of Torres' pregnancy, which prompts her husband [[Derek Shepherd]] ([[Patrick Dempsey]]) to promise that they will have a child together; Altman tells Yang that she can no longer teach her; Sloan and Robbins bond over their shared parenthood. Later, as Robbins keeps a vigil by Torres' bedside, the hallucinatory Torres is able to rouse her recovering self. As she regains consciousness, Torres accepts Robbins' proposal.

==Production==
===Conception===
Since ''Grey's Anatomy'' began, series creator [[Shonda Rhimes]] had planned to produce a musical episode. She first vocalized the idea during filming of the pilot episode, when the program was as yet untitled.<ref name="GM">{{cite web|url=http://www.greyswriters.com/2011/03/shonda-rhimes-on-song-beneath-the-song.html|title=Shonda Rhimes on "Song Beneath The Song"...|last=Rhimes|first=Shonda|authorlink=Shonda Rhimes|date=March 31, 2011|work=Grey Matter|publisher=[[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]]|accessdate=April 12, 2011}}</ref> Rhimes felt that seasons [[Grey's Anatomy (season 6)|six]] and [[Grey's Anatomy (season 7)|seven]] were the right time for the crew to "try anything and everything [they had] always wanted to do," and explained that she "finally [had] the right idea and the right talent to make [a musical episode] happen."<ref name="TVG">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Greys-Shonda-Rhimes-1025983.aspx|title=Exclusive: Shonda Rhimes Reveals Grey's Anatomy Musical Details|last=Abrams|first=Natalie|date=November 22, 2010|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref> Filming began seven and a half years after Rhimes initially raised the idea.<ref name="GM"/> Though cast member Dempsey jokingly referred to the episode as ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]] M.D.'',<ref name="WK">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvguide.com/News/Kecks-Exclusives-Greys-1030106.aspx|title=Keck's Exclusives: Grey's Musical Goes Back to Its Roots|last=Keck|first=William|date=February 28, 2011|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref> Rhimes intended for it to differ from other [[:Category:Musical television episodes|musical television episodes]].<ref name="TVG"/> She called it the opposite of "[[Once More, with Feeling (Buffy the Vampire Slayer)|Once More, with Feeling]]", the "all-out, show-stopping," musical episode of ''[[Buffy the Vampire Slayer (TV series)|Buffy the Vampire Slayer]]'', as she aimed to "do something that was musical without being a musical." <ref name="TVG"/>

Rhimes said she has difficulty getting the network's permission. She added: "I begged the studio people. I begged the network people. I took these people to dinner and begged. I jumped out at these people in bathrooms and begged. And they all smiled politely but what they were clearly really thinking was, 'This woman is an idiot.'"<ref name=GM/> Rhimes also explains why it took so long to produce this episode: {{cquote|Explaining what the heck took us so long is too complicated to go into here. There are a lot of reasons <U+2013> I was busy telling other awesome stories at Seattle Grace, [...] I was raising my tiny human, my musical talent involves oboe-playing and nothing else, the network thought it was the dumbest idea they<U+2019>d ever heard of and refused to do it.<ref name=GM/>}} The script was written by Rhimes in November 2010. She centered the episode around Ram<U+00ED>rez's character, Callie, and stated that the storyline would have developed regardless of whether it involved musical performances.<ref name="TVG"/> The actress used the opportunity to launch her career as a singer-songwriter; an alternate version of "The Story" is included on her [[Sara Ramirez EP|debut EP]], released four days prior to the episode's premiere.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/showtracker/2011/03/greys-anatomy-sara-ramirez-singer.html|title='Grey's Anatomy's' Sara Ramirez to sing on March 31 episode, release debut EP|last=Lewis|first=Randy|date=March 24, 2011|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|publisher=[[Tribune Company]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref> Former series regular [[Kate Walsh (actress)|Kate Walsh]] guest-starred as neonatal surgeon [[Addison Montgomery]]. The episode focuses on Callie as she hallucinates during a medical crisis.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/02/ask-ausiello-spoilers-on-true-blood-glee-gossip-girl-community-house-and-more/#more-190351|title=Ask Ausiello: Spoilers on True Blood, Glee, Gossip Girl, Community, House and More!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=February 8, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref> Former series regular [[Kate Walsh (actress)|Kate Walsh]] returned for the episode as neonatal surgeon Addison.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/01/greys-anatomy-exclusive-kate-walsh-returns/#more-187012|title=Grey's Anatomy Exclusive: Kate Walsh Returns for March 31 Musical Episode!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=January 26, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref> The episode served to improve the relationship between Mark and Arizona. Capshaw assessed that, "The traumatic circumstance leads to them having a greater understanding of each other and then appreciation, and then need for each other and desire to be in each other<U+2019>s lives. They come to care, I think, for one another."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/03/greys-anatomy-callie-arizona-proposal-preview/#more-202856|title=Grey's Anatomy: Why Did Arizona (Spoiler)? And Watch What Happens Next!|last=Mitovich|first=Matt Webb|date=March 25, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref>

===Musical performances===
[[File:Sara Ram<U+00ED>rez3.jpg|thumb|120px|left|Ram<U+00ED>rez (''pictured'') was the episode's primary vocalist.]]
Rhimes, executive producer [[Betsy Beers]] and director [[Tony Phelan]] selected songs that became famous through their use in ''Grey's Anatomy'', and chose "the most iconic ones, the ones that best suited [their] singers, and the ones that made the most sense."<ref name="TVG"/><ref name="PG"/> The multiple [[cover version]]s include the program's theme tune, "[[Cosy in the Rocket]]" by [[Psapp]].<ref name="WK"/> The primary vocalists are cast members Ram<U+00ED>rez, McKidd, Leigh and [[Chandra Wilson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/02/ask-ausiello-spoilers-on-vampire-diaries-greek-parenthood-hhimym-glee-and-more/#more-194039|title=Ask Ausiello: Spoilers on Vampire Diaries, Greek, Parenthood, HIMYM, Glee and More!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=February 22, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref> The soundtrack also includes "[[How to Save a Life (song)|How to Save a Life]]" by [[The Fray]] and "Running on Sunshine" by [[Roland Clark|Jesus Jackson]], performed as ensemble pieces by Ram<U+00ED>rez, McKidd, Wilson, Leigh, [[Daniel Sunjata]], [[Scott Foley]], [[Ellen Pompeo]], [[Justin Chambers]], Raver and Capshaw.<ref name="PG"/><ref name="CL"/> Ram<U+00ED>rez, McKidd and Wilson also perform together on [[Snow Patrol]]'s "[[Chasing Cars]]".<ref name="WK"/> Ram<U+00ED>rez is the lead vocalist on "[[The Story (song)|The Story]]" by [[Brandi Carlile]],<ref name="PG"/> and "Grace" by [[Kate Havnevik]], which also features the other female cast members, including Leigh and [[Sarah Drew]] on the chorus.<ref name="WK"/><ref name="CL"/> Capshaw duets with Ram<U+00ED>rez on [[KT Tunstall]]'s "[[Eye to the Telescope|Universe & U]]".<ref name="PG"/> Wilson is the lead vocalist on "Wait" by [[Get Set Go]], McKidd on "[[How We Operate]]" by [[Gomez (band)|Gomez]], and Leigh on [[Anna Nalick]]'s "[[Breathe (2 AM)]]".<ref name="PG"/><ref name="CL">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/03/greys-anatomy-preview-chyler-leigh/#more-202485|title=For Grey's Anatomy's Lexie, Things Get 'Steamy' and 'Awkward' With the Men In Her Life|last=Mitovich|first=Matt Webb|last2=Gelman|first2=Vlada|date=March 24, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref> 
{{quote box|width=25em|align=right|quote=When it first came up I was nervous, but at the same time I was just thinking, 'Hey, this is a really great opportunity for me to actually explore this side of me and be able to just let that go and have fun and know that I'm in a very safe and encouraging environment.' I was and I did and I had such a wonderful time.|source=Chyler Leigh's impressions on singing for the episode<ref name="wetpaint leigh">{{cite web|last=Huver|first=Scott|title=Exclusive: Chyler Leigh on the Grey's Anatomy Musical Episode and Stalking Sara Ramirez|url=http://www.wetpaint.com/greys-anatomy/articles/exclusive-chyler-leigh-on-the-greys-anatomy-musical-episode-and-stalking-sara-ramirez|work=Wetpaint|accessdate=June 20, 2012|date=March 25, 2011}}</ref>}}
Leigh told that some actors were not "adamant and excited" about singing but still had the possibility to participate in the episode.<ref name="TWoP">{{cite web|last=Monez|first=Mindy|title=Chyler Leigh on Grey's Anatomy's Musical Episode: 'This Is So Not About Glee'|url=http://www.televisionwithoutpity.com/telefile/2011/03/chyler-leigh-on-greys-anatomys.php|work=The Telefile Blog|publisher=[[Television Without Pity]]|accessdate=June 20, 2012|date=March 30, 2011}}</ref> "There were certain ways in which the scenes were written, even if there was a song in there, that perhaps a line was spoken instead of sung," she said.<ref name="TWoP"/> 

A coach vocal was enlisted to help the cast.<ref name="wetpaint leigh"/> Music director Chris Hovarth was recruited to arrange the selected songs for the cast. The arrangements took around two months, with vocals recorded over four days in February 2011.<ref name="PG">{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard.com/news/grey-s-anatomy-musical-episode-to-feature-1005070342.story#/news/grey-s-anatomy-musical-episode-to-feature-1005070342.story|title='Grey's Anatomy' Musical Episode to Feature Cast Singing Fray, Snow Patrol|last=Gallo|first=Phil|date=March 11, 2011|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|publisher=[[Prometheus Global Media]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref><ref name="MWM">{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/02/greys-anatomy-kevin-mckidd-director/#more-188684|title=Grey's Anatomy's Kevin McKidd Previews 'Trouble Ahead' For Owen and Cristina|last=Mitovich|first=Matt Webb|date=February 2, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref> Hovarth praised the cast's response to the episode, noting that only four performers had "serious vocal talent", while some had "barely sung in the shower" before.<ref name="PG"/> Those with professional singing experience include Ram<U+00ED>rez, who won a [[Tony Award]] for her role in the musical ''[[Spamalot]]'', and Wilson, who appeared in the [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]] production of ''[[Caroline, or Change]]''.<ref name="PG"/> Cast members' reactions toward the episode varied. Pompeo initially deemed the idea "crazy", but rescinded her stance following the first read-through.<ref name="WK"/> Recurring cast member Sunjata stated that singing was "a bit out of [his] comfort zone," but found it an "interesting challenge,"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/03/ask-ausiello-spoilers-on-fringe-house-greys-anatomy-true-blood-glee-and-more/#more-198386|title=Ask Ausiello: Spoilers on Fringe, House, Grey's Anatomy, True Blood, Glee and More!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=March 8, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref> and McKidd deemed it "very exciting to do something that's completely out on a limb for the show."<ref name="MWM"/>

==Reception==
===Pre-broadcast commentary===
Critical response prior to broadcast was mixed. ''[[TVLine]]''{{'s}} [[Michael Ausiello]] assessed that the episode would "either be a show-stopping triumph or a spectacular failure," with no possible middle ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tvline.com/2011/01/ask-ausiello-spoilers-on-house-the-office-glee-ncis-90210-bones-and-more/#more-186778|title=Ask Ausiello: Spoilers on House, The Office, Glee, NCIS, 90210, Bones and More!|last=Ausiello|first=Michael|authorlink=Michael Ausiello|date=January 25, 2011|work=[[TVLine]]|publisher=[[Mail.com Media]]|accessdate=March 25, 2011}}</ref> William Keck of ''[[TV Guide]]'' initially had "serious doubts", which were allayed by a visit to the set, during which he listened to the soundtrack. Keck likened it to the "much-beloved early seasons of ''Grey''{{'s}}, when music played a vital role on the show."<ref name="WK"/> ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''{{'s}} Dan Snierson predicted heavy use of [[Auto Tune]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ew.com/ew/article/0,,20446730,00.html|title=Dan Snierson's Hit List|last=Snierson|first=Dan|date=December 3, 2010|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=March 23, 2011}}</ref> though fellow ''EW'' writer Jennifer Armstrong was optimistic that the episode would be a success, commenting: "I have faith. I like musicals, I like ''Grey''{{'s}}. I'm rooting for this to work."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvrecaps.ew.com/recap/greys-anatomy-season-7-episode-17/|title='Grey's Anatomy' recap: Trials and Tribulations|last=Armstrong|first=Jennifer|date=March 25, 2011|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|publisher=[[Time, Inc]]|accessdate=March 26, 2011}}</ref>

===Ratings===
During its original broadcast, "Song Beneath the Song" was watched by an average of 13.09&nbsp;million American viewers. It attained a 4.9/13 [[Nielsen ratings#Ratings/share and total viewers|Nielsen rating/share]] in the [[Nielsen ratings#Demographics|18<U+2013>49 demographic]], making it the second highest-rated program of the night, behind only ''[[American Idol]]'' on the [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]] network. The rating was the second highest of the seventh season until that point, and a 30 percent increase from the previous episode, "This is How We Do It", which was watched by 2.4&nbsp;million fewer viewers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://tvbythenumbers.zap2it.com/2011/04/01/tv-ratings-thursday-rising-american-idol-leads-fox-win-musical-greys-anatomy-sings-mobbed-stomps-csi-big-bang-theory-hits-season-low/87864|title=TV Ratings Thursday: Rising 'American Idol' Leads Fox Win; Musical 'Grey's Anatomy' Sings; 'Mobbed' Stomps 'CSI'; 'Big Bang,' 'Rules' Hit Lows|last=Gorman|first=Bill|date=April 1, 2011|publisher=TV by the Numbers|accessdate=April 1, 2011}}</ref>

In Canada, where the episode also aired on March 31, 2011, it was watched by 3.18&nbsp;million viewers. Viewership again increased on "This is How We Do It", which attained 2.63&nbsp;million viewers. However, while the preceding episode was the most-viewed scripted show for the week of its original broadcast, "Song Beneath the Song" ranked second, behind ''[[The Big Bang Theory]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbm.ca/_documents/top_30_tv_programs_english/2011/nat03212011.pdf|title=Top Programs <U+2013> Total Canada (English):  March 21 - March 27, 2011|publisher=[[BBM Canada]]|accessdate=April 8, 2011|format=PDF}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bbm.ca/_documents/top_30_tv_programs_english/2011/nat03282011.pdf|title=Top Programs <U+2013> Total Canada (English):  March 28 - April 3, 2011|publisher=[[BBM Canada]]|accessdate=April 8, 2011|format=PDF}}</ref>

===Post-broadcast commentary===
Following the first minutes of the drama, reactions on [[Twitter]] were mixed.<ref name="TWSJ">{{cite web|last=Little|first=Lyneka|title=<U+2018>Grey<U+2019>s Anatomy,<U+2019> Season 7, Episode 18, <U+2018>Song Beneath the Song<U+2019>: TV Recap|url=http://blogs.wsj.com/speakeasy/2011/03/31/greys-anatomy-song-beneath-the-song-tv-recap/|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|accessdate=January 2, 2012|date=March 31, 2011}}</ref> Nicole Golden from TV Fanatic gave the episode 4.5 stars out of 5.0. She found that "overall, the concept worked since music really has always played a big part in the show. Some songs were more appropriate and/or better performed than others, though". She also wrote the concept worked in part because it was new but noted "the format would probably not have the same effect if used in future episodes."<ref>{{cite web|last=Golden|first=Nicole|title=Grey's Anatomy Review: The Musical Episode|url=http://www.tvfanatic.com/2011/03/greys-anatomy-review-song-beneath-the-song/|publisher=TV Fanatic|accessdate=January 2, 2012|date=March 31, 2011}}</ref> Even though ''[[Boston Herald]]''{{'}}s critic Mark Perigard was not a fan of the concept, saying "the ''Grey's Anatomy'' event proved how tricky it is for an established show, especially a drama, to pull off a musical episode", he did like several actors' performances. He wrote "[[Chandra Wilson]] and [[Chyler Leigh]] (whom I never have anything good to say about) delivered some impressive vocal work. [[Eric Dane]] did some of his best acting of his career last night as an anxious father-to-be terrified he would lose his best friend."<ref>{{cite web|last=Powers|first=Lindsay|title="Grey's Anatomy" musical episode: critics weigh in|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2011/04/01/us-greysanatomy-idUSTRE7306A220110401|work=[[Reuters]]|accessdate=January 2, 2012|date=April 1, 2011}}</ref> Lyneka Little of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' wrote, "If ''[[Glee (TV series)|Glee]]'' and [[ER (TV series)|''ER'']] had a baby it would be tonight<U+2019>s episode of the medical drama ''Grey<U+2019>s Anatomy''  titled <U+201C>Song Beneath the Song.<U+201D>"<ref name="TWSJ" /> In his review of the episode [[Alan Sepinwall]] of [[HitFix]] wrote "Like ''Grey's Anatomy'' as a whole, some parts were unintentionally silly, others were surprisingly powerful, and it was rarely dull, at least."<ref>{{cite web|last=Sepinwall|first=Alan|title=Review: 'Grey's Anatomy' - 'The Song Beneath the Song': How to save a life|url=http://www.hitfix.com/blogs/whats-alan-watching/posts/greys-anatomy-the-song-beneath-the-song-how-to-save-a-life|publisher=[[HitFix]]|accessdate=January 2, 2012|date=April 1, 2011}}</ref>

[[Patrick Dempsey]] admitted the musical episode may not have been showrunner [[Shonda Rhimes]]' best idea. "It's very difficult to keep it fresh when you're doing 24 
episodes a year. Shonda Rhimes has a lot of ideas, and she is in a position where she can take more chances. Sometimes that works, sometimes it does not. Last year we had the singing episode, which I think was a big mistake. But you have to try."<ref>{{cite web|last=Thompson|first=Arienne|title=Dempsey on 'Grey's' exit: 'Nice to have a job'|url=http://content.usatoday.com/communities/entertainment/post/2011/12/dempsey-on-greys-exit-nice-to-have-a-job-/1|work=[[USA Today]]|accessdate=January 2, 2012|date=December 28, 2011}}</ref>

===Accolades===
In 2011, the episode was ranked  number 19 on the [[TV Guide Network]] special, ''25 Biggest TV Blunders 2''.<ref>{{Cite episode | title = 25 Biggest TV Blunders 2 | accessdate = August 30, 2011 | network = TV Guide Network | airdate = July 31, 2011 | quote = Grey's Anatomy: The Musical?}}</ref> It was included in ''TV Guide''{{'}}s list "The Worst of 2011" saying, "Sara Ramirez has powerhouse pipes, but what this episode desperately needed was a better playlist".<ref>{{cite web|title=The Worst of 2011 - Grey's Anatomy Musical Episode|url=http://www.tvguide.com/special/best-of-year-2011/PhotoGallery/Best-Year-Worst-1039971#1039974|work=[[TV Guide]]|accessdate=December 17, 2011}}</ref> [[BuddyTV]], however, ranked it number 43 on its list of 2011's 50 Best TV Episodes and it also appeared on [[Digital Spy]]'s shortlist of "TV's Best Musical Episodes".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.buddytv.com/slideshows/friday-night-lights/the-50-best-tv-episodes-of-2011-5525.aspx|title=The 50 Best TV Episodes of 2011 |publisher=[[BuddyTV]]|accessdate=January 14, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=TV's Best Musical Episodes: Friday Fiver|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/ustv/tubetalk/a367686/tvs-best-musical-episodes-friday-fiver.html|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=May 11, 2012|coauthors=Morgan Jeffery, Catriona Wightman|date=February 24, 2012}}</ref> Supervising Music Editor Jennifer Barak and Music Editors Carli Barber and Jessica Harrison were nominated in the Best Sound Editing: Short Form Musical in Television category at the 2012 [[Motion Picture Sound Editors#The Golden Reel Awards|Golden Reel Awards]] for their work on the episode.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mpse.org/goldenreels/2012awards/pdf/TV_Short_Musical.pdf|title=Motion Picture Sound Editors Golden Reel Awards|publisher=[[Motion Picture Sound Editors]]|accessdate=February 9, 2012}}</ref>

